[4] Romania
Date: Tue 7 Mar 2017
Source: Outbreak News Today [edited]
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/romania-measles-outbreak-tops-3000-linked-eu-outbreaks-17562/


Romania: Measles outbreak tops 3000, linked to other EU outbreaks
-----------------------------------------------------------------
In a follow-up on the ongoing measles outbreak in Romania, the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) reports that from September 2016 to 17 Feb 2017 the Romanian National Institute of Public Health received reports of 3071 cases of measles.

Despite efforts to get the outbreak under control (lowered the age for administering the 1st vaccine dose from the usual 12 months to 9 months and recommended that all children up to 9 years of age are vaccinated), the outbreak continues.

To date, 16 deaths have been reported, all of which occurred in persons who were immunocompromised or had other co-morbidities. Cases have been reported in 36 districts.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The ECDC (European Center for Disease Control and Prevention) reports that between 1 Feb 2016 and 31 Jan 2017, ECDC received reports of 4484 cases of measles from 30 EU/EEA countries. In 2016, measles outbreaks were seen in a number of EU/EEA countries and an increase in the number of cases continues to be observed in 2017. Previous and ongoing measles outbreaks in 3 other EU countries have been epidemiologically-linked to the current outbreak in Romania, however further investigations are needed to gain more insights into the epidemiological links.

Immunisation is the only effective preventive measure against acquiring measles. The latest available data from WHO (from 2015) show that vaccination coverage for measles-containing vaccine was above the 95 per cent target in 17 countries for the 1st dose and 8 countries for the 2nd dose. Given that the vaccination coverage target is still to be reached in a number of EU/EEA countries, the risk of spread and sustained transmission from areas where measles transmission is occurring in areas with susceptible populations is high.

All countries in the EU/EEA have measles vaccination policies in place with 2 doses using an MMR vaccine. Catch-up programmes for individuals having missed vaccination or being too old to have been targeted by routine programmes exist in a number of countries. Strengthening routine immunisation through facilitating access to vaccination, and mechanisms to identify unvaccinated or incompletely vaccinated are needed. Promoting and providing additional opportunities for immunisation through a variety of supplemental immunisation activities may be needed in countries with suboptimal vaccination coverage and/or pockets of susceptible populations. (Excerpted from http://bit.ly/2mwDDFr)

However, even with the strong national response to the measles outbreak, a very strong anti-vaccination campaign has been reported in Romania, leading to vaccination rates with the measles-mumps-rubella (MMR) vaccine falling from 95 per cent of children in 2013 to 80 per cent in 2016, and continuing to drop. See ProMED-mail. Measles update (06) 20170201.4808554. - Mod.LK

Maps of Romania can be seen at http://www.geoatlas.com/medias/maps/countries/romania/ro111aa/romania_pol.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4888914,122. - Mod.LK]

******
[5] Recommended reading: anti-vaxxers
Date: Wed 8 Mar 2017
Source: Healio Infectious Disease News, Outbreak Tracker. February 2017
http://bit.ly/2m3ME9w


ref: Pollack MP, Kaye D. Anti-vaxxers': a menace to public health. Healio Infectious Disease News, Feb 2017
------------------------------------------------------------------
[This new opinion paper presents an excellent discussion of the risk to public health posed by those who refuse vaccination of their children, particularly with MMR vaccine. These individuals decrease the level of herd immunity, which would otherwise protect those who are too young to be vaccinated or unable to be vaccinated because of co-morbidities or immunosuppression. Equally importantly, they place themselves at increased risk of severe disease.

Before a measles vaccine became available in 1963, 3-4 million people in the United States were infected with measles each year, resulting in an estimated 48 000 hospitalizations and 400 to 500 deaths (CDC). Measles is still endemic in other countries, which pose a risk through infected travelers even to countries where local transmission of measles has been largely eliminated. Almost all of the measles outbreaks in the developed world reported by ProMED-mail are the consequence of infected individuals from endemic countries introducing the virus into the non-immune subset of largely vaccinated populations. But if the anti-vaccination sentiment builds, larger outbreaks and an increase in serious disease are a distinct possibility.

It is imperative to educate the public to the importance of maintaining a high level of vaccine coverage. This paper makes a strong case and should be shared by pediatricians and schools with parents who refuse vaccination. - Mod.LK]

